WEBVTT

00:00.098 --> 00:06.108
Our youth are not here because they are probably heading home at this point.

00:06.128 --> 00:08.091
They've been a camp or all weekend.

00:08.993 --> 00:16.525
They are up at Skycroft rebooting and I was up there on Friday night and they are having a wonderful time.

00:16.565 --> 00:24.338
I hope you've been in prayer for them and we certainly should be praying for their safe return given the weather.

00:24.610 --> 00:26.154
They have had a wonderful weekend.

00:26.856 --> 00:32.572
Parents, I invite you to engage your kids, ask them, you know, would you hear or would you learn?

00:32.852 --> 00:37.906
And more importantly, were you beginning transformation?

00:38.498 --> 00:46.506
A couple of other things as we get started here is we indeed wrapped up our worship, our week of worship and prayer.

00:46.526 --> 00:47.407
It was a wonderful time.

00:48.167 --> 01:00.699
I imagine many of you, most of you got an email about a wonderful encounter that happened on Tuesday night with a homeless gentleman, Paul, who came up here and met us and we prayed for him.

01:01.300 --> 01:07.666
And then that evening we happened to just be praying about that very matter.

01:07.810 --> 01:13.060
powerful night and really the whole week was a powerful week.

01:13.361 --> 01:25.906
And so my hope is as Pat prayed, which is that this week and this whole year is a year of transformation, a year where we as a church are setting our sights on

01:25.986 --> 01:28.970
who God is making us into together.

01:29.031 --> 01:43.051
And my hope is that in your homes, you're doing this as an individual, in your marriages, you're doing this as a marriage, as a family, doing this as a family, and then collectively as a church and prayerfully as a nation and a world.

01:43.132 --> 01:44.714
We need some transformation out there.

01:45.956 --> 01:50.162
Before we get started in the sermon, let's go ahead and start with some prayer.

01:50.978 --> 01:54.083
Heavenly Father, I invite you into this place.

01:54.183 --> 02:04.519
Holy Spirit, we desire for you to stir within us the work of transformation that you are so desirous of doing within each of us.

02:05.300 --> 02:15.836
May we not settle for our small lives, but instead, Lord, may we seek what your will is, your grand and beautiful design for each and every one of our lives.

02:16.457 --> 02:19.602
And we pray this in Christ's holy name, amen.

02:20.194 --> 02:28.247
We ended last week, or I ended last week, by saying, you know, or kind of posing the question, like, how does transformation happen?

02:29.188 --> 02:44.794
I actually, so we were talking about a little bit this morning in Sunday morning Bible study, and John at one point said something like, here's how it happens, and I immediately perked up, and I was like, oh great, John's gonna tell us how this works.

02:45.254 --> 02:47.538
And,

02:47.618 --> 03:03.879
He sort of did but he also I mean there's no one answer right is kind of the whole thing I in fact I do invite I want to invite each and every one of you in this moment and kind of as you're thinking through the week like How do you think like how do you think it happens?

03:04.399 --> 03:05.461
How do people grow?

03:05.521 --> 03:09.586
How do people mature into the?

03:09.698 --> 03:17.952
Folks that like hopefully you've got someone in your mind who's like a pillar of the faith or is a human being you would want to admire and live up to.

03:18.453 --> 03:21.598
What did they do to become that?

03:22.039 --> 03:24.944
More than just like God did a work in them.

03:24.984 --> 03:27.027
That is like super important obviously.

03:27.548 --> 03:32.596
But there's ways in which they walked through this world to become the person that they became.

03:32.977 --> 03:35.922
If you've got something, I invite you now.

03:36.354 --> 03:46.429
Email me, call me, text me, reach out in some fashion, and you tell me what made that person, that person, because I'd love to know.

03:46.669 --> 03:52.618
And just fair warning, I might share it in a future sermon unless you don't want me to.

03:54.781 --> 03:59.348
I'm going to try to answer that question how in this sermon.

03:59.888 --> 04:03.794
And it's a partial answer, right?

04:03.874 --> 04:08.579
And the answer, if put as simply as possible, is this.

04:08.739 --> 04:11.402
You become what you behold.

04:11.462 --> 04:14.966
You become what you behold.

04:16.467 --> 04:30.482
Whatever it is that you're looking at and paying attention to and ingesting on a daily, regular basis is going to have a shaping process over your lifetime.

04:31.298 --> 04:42.893
And if you keep doing that day after day after day, well, you better believe that that is how you will begin to think and receive the world and see the world.

04:42.953 --> 04:45.657
And so I want to start with two examples.

04:45.817 --> 04:55.410
The first is, well, maybe it's less of an example, but it's more of a, like two people seeing the same thing in a very different way.

04:56.610 --> 05:00.596
I was going to give you the 2015 meme of the black and blue dress.

05:00.816 --> 05:02.378
Do you remember this one?

05:02.398 --> 05:03.560
I'm going a different route though.

05:04.060 --> 05:19.342
When I was living in Alabama there, like I preached a sermon, we used to give these bulletins out and you'd fold them like this and there'd be like Uniontown Baptist Church sitting on the front and then inside of it, you would have the order of worship, right?

05:19.642 --> 05:25.330
Well, on this one this week, I produced one of those optical illusions

05:25.474 --> 05:25.774
Right?

05:26.295 --> 05:33.662
And then the optical illusion was the object lesson for the day.

05:33.702 --> 05:45.574
And the object lesson was simply to say that like one part of the picture, though it looked black, or though it looked white, was actually black or gray, right?

05:46.015 --> 05:50.499
And so you would look at it and you think, oh, that is, that's white.

05:51.060 --> 05:53.522
And then I would say, well, no, it's not.

05:54.050 --> 05:57.726
And then I'd say, OK, go ahead and just fold your paper over.

05:57.806 --> 06:00.136
And you can see that it's not that color.

06:00.196 --> 06:04.434
You think it's that color, but it's not that color.

06:05.634 --> 06:18.193
A nice older lady, her name is Shelby, came up to me afterward and she said, I think my program is defective because mine is white and maybe everybody else is not.

06:19.094 --> 06:25.744
And I said to her, Shelby, I assure you, I just ran them all through a printer and you got the same thing that everybody else did.

06:26.566 --> 06:32.114
You need to understand that this is not white, it's actually black, right?

06:32.194 --> 06:34.197
And it wouldn't soak in.

06:34.338 --> 06:39.446
And so she's seeing one thing, but she thinks she's seeing another thing, right?

06:41.810 --> 06:43.192
Maybe more to the point.

06:43.313 --> 06:48.902
And here, I think I need to stir the pot a little bit, maybe a lot of it.

06:49.663 --> 06:53.590
There's been a big news event that's happened in the last week or so.

06:54.431 --> 06:56.575
And there was a woman who was shot.

06:57.116 --> 06:58.578
Her name is Renee Good.

06:59.554 --> 07:06.961
And when she was shot and killed, I was shocked.

07:08.382 --> 07:16.490
I was shocked by how divided the two responses were to this moment in history.

07:17.771 --> 07:29.042
And my goal right now is not to wade into one or the other response, is to make sure we're all seeing the two responses.

07:30.210 --> 07:42.862
Because when I looked at the responses, the one was, this is a deeply tragic moment where a woman was shot and killed and she has a six year old that has now been left behind.

07:43.923 --> 07:44.664
And that's awful.

07:46.266 --> 07:58.898
And then the other response was she was a domestic terrorist and she was in the way of impeding the work of the federal agent

07:59.106 --> 08:01.470
And she should not have been there.

08:01.770 --> 08:03.172
I've heard this, right?

08:03.192 --> 08:05.355
And so there are these two responses.

08:06.878 --> 08:07.979
And they're sitting in the world.

08:08.019 --> 08:12.466
And this side cannot understand this side.

08:13.708 --> 08:17.774
And this side cannot seem to understand this side, right?

08:17.814 --> 08:28.370
Again, my goal is not to wade into one or the other and to tell you which reality is true, the black or the white here.

08:30.338 --> 08:46.742
My real goal is to say that if I were to talk to this side, I could probably tell you what sorts of media sources they're listening to, who is shaping and forming them, right?

08:47.524 --> 08:52.251
And then if I were to talk to this side, I would be able to tell you the exact same thing.

08:52.271 --> 08:57.298
And I would tell you, well, they're watching these shows and they're listening to these speakers.

08:58.946 --> 09:06.734
And you have to realize that both of these things, it's like we live in two different worlds.

09:07.654 --> 09:12.639
And they're both forming whichever world you choose to live in.

09:14.581 --> 09:27.954
And I would encourage you as the church to unplug from these two worlds, especially in terms of how we understand our politics and understand reality and to plug yourself into the ways

09:28.034 --> 09:38.689
And that Jesus teaches us to think about the way the world should work and the way that we should be walking through this world.

09:41.893 --> 09:45.378
Jesus' ways are not the ways of the world.

09:45.398 --> 09:49.664
And I apply that to really both of these camps here.

09:50.865 --> 09:57.234
And we have to learn to be critical thinkers if we are going to walk through this world well.

10:00.098 --> 10:08.609
more to the point, if we are going to walk through this world as people who have been transformed into the image of Christ.

10:12.294 --> 10:21.327
We read 2 Corinthians 3, and I want to read for you the transformation part of this passage.

10:22.428 --> 10:29.778
Here Paul says, we all, with unveiled face, we behold

10:30.082 --> 10:32.245
the glory of the Lord.

10:33.466 --> 10:41.196
And what happens when you behold the glory of the Lord, of the God who created the heavens and the earth?

10:41.356 --> 10:44.280
What happens when you look into God's face?

10:44.300 --> 10:54.994
Well, he goes on to say, we are transformed into the same image, which is the goal, right?

10:56.034 --> 11:05.831
to become, to be transformed into that image from one degree of glory to another.

11:06.772 --> 11:10.779
For this comes from the Lord who is the Spirit.

11:16.369 --> 11:19.514
Recently, I was asked to serve on the North Star board.

11:20.436 --> 11:21.618
So I said yes.

11:21.986 --> 11:24.891
And I had my first meeting with them in December.

11:24.931 --> 11:33.286
And then just on Thursday, they said, well, they called another meeting and we had a strategic planning session.

11:33.827 --> 11:37.033
And so we all gathered together at Columbia Church.

11:37.654 --> 11:40.920
And they were like, we'll say 15 to 20 of us in the room.

11:40.940 --> 11:46.450
And we were strategically planning what North Star should do.

11:46.818 --> 11:52.346
for the rest of 2026, what are the focuses that they want to have, right?

11:53.067 --> 12:00.458
And one of the key ones that they want to work on is discipleship, which I take to be another word for transformation.

12:01.340 --> 12:05.265
Discipleship is the work of how do we become a transformed people.

12:05.726 --> 12:08.370
And so as we're talking about discipleship,

12:08.834 --> 12:11.937
They gave us an article to read in advance.

12:12.217 --> 12:19.084
A gentleman by the name of Carrie Newhoff wrote an article that says, this is clickbait if there ever was.

12:19.364 --> 12:21.046
He's good at coming up with these titles.

12:21.486 --> 12:24.509
Seven disruptive trends that will rule 2026.

12:24.569 --> 12:27.252
This is the name of the article.

12:27.272 --> 12:28.113
This is a very good article.

12:29.414 --> 12:33.378
Seven disruptive trends that will rule 2026.

12:35.520 --> 12:37.362
And rule number five,

12:37.602 --> 12:39.384
is the one I want to talk about today.

12:39.424 --> 12:49.597
He says, and I wholeheartedly agree, that discipleship is now largely controlled by algorithm.

12:51.199 --> 12:54.624
Discipleship is largely controlled by algorithm.

12:55.184 --> 12:56.726
Do you know what he means by that?

12:58.549 --> 12:59.330
Maybe, maybe not.

13:00.872 --> 13:01.793
Well, then let me tell you.

13:03.535 --> 13:05.938
It means that when you hop onto your computer,

13:06.818 --> 13:09.843
Google knows exactly what you want to hear.

13:09.863 --> 13:11.986
It has been studying you.

13:12.006 --> 13:14.670
It has been measuring you.

13:14.690 --> 13:17.294
It knows every fine detail.

13:17.434 --> 13:20.839
It knows things about you that you don't know about you.

13:20.879 --> 13:22.862
And so what does it want to do?

13:22.882 --> 13:30.674
It wants to feed you what you want, because at the end of the day, it wants you to be happy with it.

13:31.490 --> 13:36.636
And so do you think Google is going to feed you things that upset you, at least like internally?

13:36.676 --> 13:41.582
No, they're not going to feed you things that will challenge your world view.

13:41.622 --> 13:44.004
They will instead feed you what?

13:44.585 --> 13:47.789
The things you already want to hear, the things you already believe.

13:49.070 --> 13:55.698
And so your discipleship in this way, and what Kerry Newhoff is saying, is that you are getting on to Google

13:55.874 --> 13:59.780
And you're just hearing the same voices again and again and again.

13:59.840 --> 14:02.984
And they're already telling you the things that you want to hear.

14:04.927 --> 14:09.694
And then you come into a church sanctuary and you hear a pastor on a Sunday morning, you hear me speak.

14:11.116 --> 14:19.588
And I might say something that you disagree with that actually challenges your world order.

14:20.489 --> 14:23.634
And you find, well, that's a little uncomfortable.

14:23.778 --> 14:26.181
I'm not so sure about that.

14:26.481 --> 14:29.685
Because all week long, I've been hearing these other things.

14:29.766 --> 14:33.951
And all week long, I've been listening to these other pastors who say these things.

14:35.453 --> 14:37.836
And I kind of like what they have to say.

14:37.876 --> 14:49.330
And so discipleship, it's being ruled by the algorithms that connect your Facebook and your Instagram and your Twitter feed.

14:49.858 --> 14:53.502
and they continue to feed the same thing over and over.

14:53.562 --> 15:02.593
And so what happens is there was, well, kind of the quote of that morning was the gentleman who was sitting next to me, his name was Oliver.

15:02.613 --> 15:08.721
And Oliver is an older African-American preacher who I think is now retired.

15:09.422 --> 15:10.883
And he had the phrase of the day.

15:10.923 --> 15:14.368
And he said, the people aren't looking for transformation.

15:14.428 --> 15:17.311
He said, they're looking for validation.

15:18.192 --> 15:19.634
They're looking for validation.

15:20.098 --> 15:21.120
And I thought, that's right.

15:22.642 --> 15:30.173
We're all looking for, I go online or maybe even like conversations with friends.

15:30.253 --> 15:33.237
And what I'm looking for is not for them to challenge me.

15:33.257 --> 15:36.923
I want them to validate what I already believe.

15:38.125 --> 15:41.169
And the algorithms are very good at doing this.

15:42.992 --> 15:49.842
But if we are going to participate in transformation, we need to learn to get a little uncomfortable.

15:50.626 --> 16:03.887
We need to learn to let other people, other ideas challenge what we think, who we are, and to really create some space to say, maybe I was wrong about this issue.

16:04.568 --> 16:06.551
Let's work on that together.

16:07.373 --> 16:13.202
Let me find people who disagree with me and seek

16:13.410 --> 16:21.203
See if we can't come to some kind of common ground or see if I can't somehow understand who they are.

16:25.710 --> 16:36.808
I know it might feel like I'm kind of hitting big tech and Facebook and Google and these guys a little too much today.

16:38.211 --> 16:40.274
But I'm going to keep going.

16:42.434 --> 16:46.039
Big tech has learned how to hack your brain.

16:46.279 --> 16:59.936
You've probably, some of you have heard this, some of you may have not, and I'm talking to both of you of course, but especially if you've never heard this before, you need to know that this is how the internet works, this is how these tech companies work.

16:59.956 --> 17:07.666
You see, they've cracked something about the human brain that we didn't like fully know before.

17:08.226 --> 17:11.249
There's a part of your brain in the back called the limbic system.

17:11.829 --> 17:14.772
And it is, we'll call it like the animal nature.

17:14.832 --> 17:19.797
And all animals have a limbic system, like the least of the animal.

17:19.817 --> 17:22.159
And the limbic system is meant for fight or flight.

17:22.900 --> 17:26.643
It teaches us our desires, like your base desires, that is.

17:27.544 --> 17:31.108
So you should think in terms of like, what makes me angry?

17:31.468 --> 17:34.251
Well, when it does, it's sitting back there in that limbic system.

17:34.991 --> 17:37.874
Your desire for sex, back in the limbic system.

17:38.274 --> 17:51.953
Anything that is like helping the survival of the species, back there in the limbic system, what separates humans from every other species is what sits up here, the prefrontal cortex.

17:52.754 --> 18:05.732
And that part, that allows us to sit back and to think about things and to say, oh, I'm not so sure that's right or let's reason through this or emotional regulation.

18:05.853 --> 18:06.834
It's all up here.

18:07.874 --> 18:23.821
But here's what the tech companies have figured out that you and I need to get wise to is they've learned how to override this human part, the thing that makes us most human and tap directly into the thing that makes us most animal.

18:25.204 --> 18:26.045
And so what do they do?

18:26.947 --> 18:33.618
It highlights fear and aggression and sex and all of the things

18:33.730 --> 18:42.959
that you can imagine coming through your screen when you open up Facebook or TikTok or any of these, right?

18:43.400 --> 18:50.567
It's all right there, making you want to click these buttons.

18:51.688 --> 18:55.432
And what they're aiming for is not your humanity.

18:56.173 --> 19:01.138
They're aiming for the thing that makes you least human and most animal.

19:04.930 --> 19:09.800
If my thesis is right, that you become what you behold.

19:09.840 --> 19:22.866
Our tech companies are trying to get us to behold things that make us less human and more animal day after day after day.

19:23.426 --> 19:45.793
And if I were to put up here like a chart of how much time humans have spent on their screen, like, and you just kind of start it back in 2000 and you measure it to 2026, you would see that line just go up and up and up and up because we're spending more and more and more time staring at the very things that we're turning into.

19:45.813 --> 19:50.258
And we wonder why we have a partisan problem, right?

19:50.338 --> 19:52.941
We wonder why everybody's so anxious.

19:53.282 --> 19:55.504
We wonder why people are depressed.

19:55.525 --> 19:59.149
We wonder why all of these problems are going on around us.

20:01.252 --> 20:03.334
We'll look no further than what we behold.

20:04.255 --> 20:12.386
If we are beholding these things day in, day out, over time, that changes us.

20:13.227 --> 20:18.994
And I say us collectively as a nation and a world, and I say us as a church,

20:19.714 --> 20:22.760
But what I really want you to think about is you.

20:22.800 --> 20:25.726
Is it changing you?

20:25.807 --> 20:37.751
Is what you behold somehow warping, changing who you are and who you're becoming.

20:39.335 --> 20:40.978
And if we're going to do the

20:41.058 --> 20:50.492
spiritual work, the good work of transformation as we want to, as somebody moved into the mind of Christ, the image of God.

20:51.294 --> 20:58.324
Well, it's going to take a very different kind of beholding than what the tech companies are trying to get us to do.

20:58.364 --> 21:07.378
And I repeat, 2 Corinthians 3, 18, we all

21:08.194 --> 21:14.400
with the veils of our faces removed, we are beholding the glory of God.

21:14.900 --> 21:37.362
And when we behold His magnificence, the character of God who is loving, this character of God who is for us, the character of God who sees a world in a desperate place and wants to do something about it, well then when we behold that, we are transformed into the same image

21:37.442 --> 21:40.767
from one degree of glory to another.

21:40.787 --> 21:48.258
I want to tell you a story about hummingbirds.

21:50.942 --> 22:01.617
There was a man who went to a local shop and he said, I have a hummingbird feeder, but I can't get any hummingbirds.

22:02.859 --> 22:05.042
And the store owner said, well, that's odd.

22:05.538 --> 22:07.900
because I sell a lot of these hummingbird feeders.

22:08.641 --> 22:13.526
And I know with certainty that there are hummingbirds all over the place here.

22:14.847 --> 22:18.071
And you just have to know what you're looking for.

22:19.612 --> 22:24.637
And so the man returned home and he began to look in earnest for hummingbirds.

22:25.858 --> 22:30.062
And eventually he saw one and then he saw another.

22:31.264 --> 22:33.586
Pretty soon he started seeing others

22:34.498 --> 22:37.321
And then he realized, well, they're everywhere.

22:38.302 --> 22:41.505
He'd begin to walk through the woods and start to see hummingbirds.

22:41.945 --> 22:44.267
He'd walk through neighborhoods and see hummingbirds.

22:44.928 --> 22:47.630
And he realized hummingbirds aren't nowhere.

22:47.670 --> 22:50.193
Hummingbirds are everywhere.

22:51.634 --> 23:00.262
And Scott McKnight, who wrote this, concludes this way, the movements of God's spirit is all around us.

23:01.143 --> 23:04.306
Few of us see it because we first have to learn

23:04.610 --> 23:05.411
what to look for.

23:07.173 --> 23:15.944
In a book by Martin Israel, he wrote, eternity lies all around us and only a veil prevents us from seeing it.

23:17.546 --> 23:25.375
The hum of angels surrounds us and we only need ears to hear it or eyes to see them.

23:28.499 --> 23:34.066
I think too often the veils do hide from us.

23:34.882 --> 23:38.646
who God is and what God's trying to do in this world.

23:39.467 --> 23:49.857
If we could just pierce it, we'd begin to realize that there's a different way that you and I should be transformed and live in this world.

23:53.921 --> 24:02.770
As we were going through Sunday morning Bible study, I was alerted to something that I hadn't planned on sharing, but now feel like I desperately have to.

24:03.298 --> 24:05.420
It's from Philippians chapter four.

24:06.461 --> 24:09.124
It's all about what are we watching?

24:09.184 --> 24:11.127
What are we reading?

24:11.187 --> 24:13.409
What are we ingesting?

24:13.850 --> 24:15.231
What are we beholding?

24:16.092 --> 24:32.370
And Paul says to you and to me, finally, brothers, whatever is true, whatever is honorable, whatever is just, whatever is pure, whatever is lovely,

24:33.186 --> 24:45.022
Whatever is commendable, if there is any excellence, if there is anything worthy of praise, well think about these things.

24:46.024 --> 24:47.446
Think about these things.

24:49.068 --> 25:01.906
Don't you close your eyes for a second and imagine what's been on your computer screen for the last week and ask yourself, are these true, honorable, just, lovely, pure, commendable and excellent?

25:02.370 --> 25:03.872
Are these worthy of praise?

25:05.273 --> 25:08.937
And if not, what are you beholding?

25:11.460 --> 25:14.924
And as you behold these, what are you becoming?

25:22.312 --> 25:23.433
What are we supposed to do, Eric?

25:23.974 --> 25:24.895
What are we supposed to do?

25:24.935 --> 25:31.442
I've got two things for you to conclude the service with here.

25:31.554 --> 25:32.857
The first is this.

25:32.897 --> 25:33.839
I want to make a plug.

25:34.380 --> 25:42.075
We are starting a practice on Wednesday nights, January 28, begins our Wednesday nights again.

25:42.115 --> 25:45.783
We are calling this life together.

25:47.185 --> 25:51.474
It's what we've been doing, but we just have a new name for it.

25:52.514 --> 25:56.299
Life together, though, is actually a lot behind this for me.

25:56.319 --> 25:59.903
It's a Bonhoeffer book, and there's a really good theology with it.

26:00.464 --> 26:02.306
But anyway, it is doing life together.

26:02.346 --> 26:06.591
It's adults and kids and youth, and everybody is there together.

26:06.891 --> 26:07.552
We eat a meal.

26:08.113 --> 26:11.517
And then after that, I'm going to lead a study.

26:12.438 --> 26:15.922
So this will go on for nine weeks, starting Jan 28.

26:16.034 --> 26:21.899
nine weeks, we're gonna talk about emotionally healthy spirituality is the name of this.

26:22.480 --> 26:36.453
It's somewhat provocative in this main idea, which is that until you are emotionally healthy and mature, you can't really become spiritually healthy and mature.

26:36.493 --> 26:46.002
And I think one of the biggest roadblocks, and this is the argument of the series, and it's something that I've really actually been waiting to kind of roll out

26:46.914 --> 26:59.688
One of the greatest roadblocks to transformation, spiritual transformation, I think is our inability to deal with the emotional transformation that needs to happen.

27:00.328 --> 27:06.014
And too often, our limbic system overrides what should be the front of our brain.

27:06.675 --> 27:13.042
And when it does this, we act out in ways not becoming a Christian.

27:13.634 --> 27:16.217
And so for those nine weeks, men, women will gather together.

27:16.317 --> 27:17.238
We'll probably be in here.

27:17.258 --> 27:18.660
I'll be leading it.

27:19.140 --> 27:24.707
And it's a powerful series in which I expect transformation to happen.

27:26.408 --> 27:27.109
The second thing.

27:30.393 --> 27:34.958
I was visiting my brother in early December.

27:36.580 --> 27:40.645
And he said two things that caught my attention.

27:40.725 --> 27:41.906
The first was,

27:42.178 --> 27:46.606
that he goes to church every week, which I didn't know, and made me really happy.

27:47.467 --> 27:48.849
I wasn't so sure about that.

27:49.430 --> 27:55.261
And then when he said that, I said, when you go to church, why do you go?

27:55.821 --> 27:57.024
What's your favorite part?

27:57.304 --> 27:59.628
What do you want in a church service?

28:01.631 --> 28:03.495
I'd love to ask each of you this, by the way.

28:04.977 --> 28:07.762
And he said, well, it's certainly not the sermon.

28:11.778 --> 28:16.123
He said, what it is is they offer a time of silence.

28:17.885 --> 28:19.687
He goes to a Lutheran service.

28:20.748 --> 28:22.450
They're clearly not Baptists.

28:23.992 --> 28:25.954
And he said, they offer a time of silence.

28:26.615 --> 28:40.370
And he said that some of the most sacred time, he didn't say word sacred, it's some of the time in his week where he knows he can just breathe and just be.

28:40.578 --> 28:42.561
And so here's how I want to end this service.

28:43.442 --> 28:44.524
The kids are going to come with me.

28:45.966 --> 28:48.190
Because parents, I know that you sometimes need that.

28:49.912 --> 28:52.556
And I'm going to give you 90 seconds.

28:53.538 --> 28:54.779
It doesn't sound like much.

28:55.120 --> 28:59.406
But 90 seconds of silence is going to feel like an eternity.

29:00.368 --> 29:02.892
I'm going to walk out that back door with the kids.

29:03.933 --> 29:05.396
And in 90 seconds, I'll come back.

29:06.117 --> 29:07.379
But here's what I want you doing.

29:07.899 --> 29:09.682
I want your eyes closed.

29:10.242 --> 29:17.692
And I've been saying, during the sermon here that's gone on too long, I've been saying that what you behold is what you become.

29:19.094 --> 29:23.921
And I want you to practice this, like actually practice it.

29:24.302 --> 29:27.586
I want you to close your eyes when I start the clock.

29:28.628 --> 29:38.962
And I want you to imagine Jesus, like looking into the actual face of the actual Jesus and beholding Him.

29:41.090 --> 30:09.010
and taking the veil off of your own face, whatever it is that's keeping you from Him, and to give yourself some time, to just be in His presence, and to let some things go, and to see what kind of reaction you get from Jesus, because what I think He will look at you with is very soft eyes, who love you, He loves you, and He wants the best for you.

30:09.762 --> 30:12.207
And he wants to encourage you.

30:16.655 --> 30:19.381
And he doesn't want you staring at those screens all week.

30:20.663 --> 30:21.906
All right, so here we go.

30:21.926 --> 30:25.312
1201.

30:26.575 --> 30:28.178
Children, why don't you come with me?

